        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This setup uses the maximum available sensitivity of a wide-band 3mm continuum setup.

Sensitivity

This proposal argues that in order to obtain a meaningful constraint on the YSO radio flare rate of the Orion protostars, an on-source time of about 4h with an overall 3sigma sensitivity of 20muJy is required (see text). This ensures S/N&gt;20 on timescales of ~10min. Within this time, we expect as many as 16 flares, mainly due to the sensitivity increase over previous observations. While this sensitivity will not quite be reached when pointing at the bright Orion Nebula (because of increased system temperature in spite of spatial filtering), even the radio source population that is already known (and that will be detected at high S/N) is large enough to provide a meaningful measurement.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our setup has been selected to maximize continuum sensitivity.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe BN/KL at high angular resolution. We are interested in the point source population, and the spatial filtering associated with the small synthesized beam size will help minimize the impact of extended emission from the cloud or the nebula. The configuration C36-5 with a synthesized beam size of 0.5" and an MRS of 7.8" seems ideal for this purpose and an excellent match to our VLA and Chandra data. We will use our deep high-resolution cm data of the region to help assess potential artifacts that result from emission of the nebula that 'survived' the spatial filtering.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
