    <prp:abstract>With unprecedented sensitivity at millimeter wavelengths on short timescales, ALMA is providing us with a new window on high-energy processes in Young Stellar Objects (YSOs). At these wavelengths, we have access to synchrotron radiation from electrons accelerated to MeV energies in flares, orders of magnitude more energetic than typical energies in stellar X-ray flares. In addition to probing higher energies, we also have access to the early acceleration and heating phase of a flare and not only the resulting thermal X-ray emission. At the moment, very little is known about the recurrence rate of extreme millimeter-wavelength flares in YSOs in spite of their importance for our understanding of the high-energy irradiation of protoplanetary disks and its influence on planet formation. We here propose to characterize extreme millimeter-wavelength variability of YSOs in the BN/KL region of the Orion Nebula Cluster since 1) it contains many well-studied, radio-bright YSOs, and 2) ALMA observations will complement our extensive JVLA cm-wavelength observations to much higher energies. We will also study the consequences of YSO flares for the constant-flux assumption in synthesis imaging.</prp:abstract>
